<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83"><gtr:id>3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83</gtr:id><gtr:name>University College London</gtr:name><gtr:department>Institute of Cognitive Neuroscience</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Gower Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 6BT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83"><gtr:id>3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83</gtr:id><gtr:name>University College London</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Gower Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 6BT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/A9B1866C-EE3E-4D81-A83C-118745E9433E"><gtr:id>A9B1866C-EE3E-4D81-A83C-118745E9433E</gtr:id><gtr:name>Goldsmiths College</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Lewisham Way</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>New Cross</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>SE14 6NW</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/77CFE4A5-4684-4A16-80F6-47E64F3EBAF0"><gtr:id>77CFE4A5-4684-4A16-80F6-47E64F3EBAF0</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Michael</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Joseph</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Banissy</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH004688%2F1"><gtr:id>FA7A9B4C-5337-4B66-ABB6-BA50FAAC883C</gtr:id><gtr:title>Simulation Processes in Social Cognition: The Role of 'Classical' and 'Extended' Mirror Systems</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H004688/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Observing another person performing an action, experiencing sensations or experiencing different emotions, results in activity in brain regions which are active during our own experience of the observed state (mirror systems). This cortical mirroring between observed and self-experience has been suggested to be crucial for social interactions because it enables the observer to understand the experiences of another by matching what is perceived with what it would 'feel like' to be in that situation.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The purpose of this research is to investigate the role that brain regions with mirror properties play in social perception and how these systems interact to facilitate social cognition.&amp;nbsp; This will be achieved through the use of brain imaging, brain stimulation, and neuropsychological studies. Using a combination of these approaches, the research shall investigate whether some neural systems with mirror properties are more important for social cognition than others; how they interact to aid social perception; and what impact facilitation or disruption of sensory-motor mirror mechanisms has on social perception.&amp;nbsp; The findings will develop our knowledge of the mechanisms which underpin the ability to understand the actions and behaviors of others.&lt;/p>

