 synaesthesia formed the scientific foundations of a symposium on art spectatorship at the Tate Modern funded by a Leverhulme International Network Award, and a forthcoming edited volume to be published with Oxford University Press entitled 'Mirror-touch: Thresholds of Empathy with Art'. In this regard, my research has made interdisciplinary theoretical contributions that have had a significant impact beyond my own discipline.

Additionally, my work on mirror-touch synaesthesia has also had important societal impact in terms of public and practioner awareness of this condition. Prior to my work on mirror-touch synaesthesia there was very little public and scientific awareness of the condition, with only one single case study published in the literature. My colleagues and I have lead developments in our understanding of this condition, and as a product of this, mirror-touch synaesthesia is now listed on NHS Choices website with direct citation to one of my research papers on the condition. In this context my research has influenced professional practice within external public organisations.

Finally, the work generated a considerable amount of media attention and invitations for public talks (e.g. Latitude Festival, UK) that has led to an increase in awareness of social neuroscience research and the condition of mirror-touch synaesthesia. For example, my research has been the subject of worldwide media coverage including features in New Scientist Magazine, Reuters Online, Good Morning America, Yahoo News, The Guardian, Wired, The Australian, BBC Radio 4, BBC Radio 5, National Public Radio (USA), BBC Television, Scientific American, CBS, Fox News, and The New York Times. All of which has served to engage the public with my research findings.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2012</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>8BFCCF19-0770-4938-9E00-6FF2A6A44C7F</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>5458ca7062a315.46905389</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>This one year Postdoctoral Fellowship provided support for the publication of findings from my PhD thesis and for related studies to be completed. In doing so, it resulted in nine published outputs that appeared in leading peer review journals (e.g. Current Biology, Journal of Neuroscience). Further, the findings have been presented at academic conferences, departmental seminars, and public talks (over twenty talks have been given to date). In doing so, this has led to the generation of new knowledge, the development of new research networks, and increased research capability. In relation to new knowledge, key findings related to developments in our understanding of how our sensorimotor systems contribute to social perception abilities, how inter-individual variability in our sensorimotor systems and other brain regions contribute to socio-cognitive and social perception skills, and in our understanding of neurocognitive mechanisms that give rise to a rare experience known as mirror-touch synaesthesia (where individuals experience overt sensations of touch or pain on their own body when simply observing this to another person). These findings led to broader interest from the public, media, and wider academic community, which resulted in the development of new research networks. For example, the work on mirror-touch has resulted in new interdisciplinary research networks and funded opportunities in the UK and overseas; e.g. the development of the 'Mirror-touch network' funded by the Leverhulme Trust that seek to use mirror-touch as a tool to explore the spectatorship of art. More broadly, as a Postdoctoral Fellowship the grant enabled me to gain and consolidate research skills (e.g. brain imaging, brain stimulation) and experience, which has served as a strong foundation for other successes in my academic career to date; including successful further funding related to the Fellowship, receiving a Senior Lectureship position three years after PhD completion, and leading a successful brain stimulation laboratory.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The findings provided novel insights in the field of social neuroscience, including the following topics - mirror-touch synaesthesia, emotion processing, loneliness, social perception, and social cognition. This has resulted in productive lines of research from other academic colleagues. It has also led to further successful funding applications. In this regard, the research outcomes have been taken forward through academic routes.

For non-academic routes, the main avenue in which the findings have been taken forward is through cultural impact. There have been a number of art events related to the findings from this award and symposiums at international leading art galleries (e.g. Tate Modern Symposium on 'Mirror-touch and the social'). In addition, the work generated a considerable amount of media attention (e.g. BBC Radio) and invitations for public talks (e.g. Salon London) that has led to an increase in awareness of social neuroscience research and the condition of mirror-touch synaesthesia.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>05E564AD-AA42-42F2-9A29-6E341FCCF7E2</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5458cad9805827.87192646</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>4F82AD87-CFE9-4EE8-A634-6E757CE64663</gtr:id><gtr:title>Superior facial expression, but not identity recognition in mirror-touch synaesthesia</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/4906a0766ea27f13e1a718e1639cf801"><gtr:id>4906a0766ea27f13e1a718e1639cf801</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Michael Banissy (author)</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>1900-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>r_9548666097cbd59a54</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>0A67E408-8616-4D58-B8D1-2BD323B5F517</gtr:id><gtr:title>Experiencing touch by observation : mirror-touch synaesthesia</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/4906a0766ea27f13e1a718e1639cf801"><gtr:id>4906a0766ea27f13e1a718e1639cf801</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Michael Banissy (author)</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>1900-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeI